[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] It’s been available across browsers since March 2019.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] The **`AbortController`** interface represents a controller object that allows you to abort one or more Web requests as and when desired.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] You can create a new `AbortController` object using the `AbortController()` constructor.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] Communicating with an asynchronous operation is done using an `AbortSignal` object.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] Creates a new `AbortController` object instance.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] Returns an `AbortSignal` object instance, which can be used to communicate with, or to abort, an asynchronous operation.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] Aborts an asynchronous operation before it has completed.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] This is able to abort fetch requests, consumption of any response bodies, and streams.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] See the `AbortSignal` page for usage examples.
[src:ky-fetch/abortcontroller] You can find a full working example on GitHub; you can also see it running live.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:ky-fetch/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API provides an interface for fetching resources (including across the network).
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] It is a more powerful and flexible replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API uses `Request` and `Response` objects (and other things involved with network requests), as well as related concepts such as CORS and the HTTP Origin header semantics.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] For making a request and fetching a resource, use the `fetch()` method.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] It is a global method in both `Window` and `Worker` contexts.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] This makes it available in pretty much any context you might want to fetch resources in.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method takes one mandatory argument, the path to the resource you want to fetch.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to the `Response` to that request — as soon as the server responds with headers — **even if the server response is an HTTP error status**.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] You can also optionally pass in an `init` options object as the second argument (see `Request`).
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Once a `Response` is retrieved, there are a number of methods available to define what the body content is and how it should be handled.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] You can create a request and response directly using the `Request()` and `Response()` constructors, but it's uncommon to do this directly.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Instead, these are more likely to be created as results of other API actions (for example, `FetchEvent.respondWith()` from service workers).
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Find out more about using the Fetch API features in Using Fetch.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] The `fetchLater()` API enables a developer to request a *deferred fetch*, that can be sent after a specified period of time, or when the page is closed or navigated away from.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method used to fetch a resource.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Represents the set of options that can be used to configure a deferred fetch request.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Represents the result of requesting a deferred fetch.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Represents response/request headers, allowing you to query them and take different actions depending on the results.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Controls the top-level quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:ky-fetch/api-fetch-api] Controls the shared cross-origin subframe quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] It’s been available across browsers since March 2017.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] The **`Response`** interface of the Fetch API represents the response to a request.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] You can create a new `Response` object using the `Response()` constructor, but you are more likely to encounter a `Response` object being returned as the result of another API operation—for example, a service worker `FetchEvent.respondWith`, or a simple `fetch()`.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] A `ReadableStream` of the body contents.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Stores a boolean value that declares whether the body has been used in a response yet.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] The `Headers` object associated with the response.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] A boolean indicating whether the response was successful (status in the range `200` – `299`) or not.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Indicates whether or not the response is the result of a redirect (that is, its URL list has more than one entry).
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] The status message corresponding to the status code.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] The type of the response (e.g., `basic`, `cors`).
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a new `Response` object associated with a network error.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a new response with a different URL.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a new `Response` object for returning the provided JSON encoded data.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with an `ArrayBuffer` representation of the response body.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Blob` representation of the response body.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Uint8Array` representation of the response body.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a `FormData` representation of the response body.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with the result of parsing the response body text as `JSON`.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Returns a promise that resolves with a text representation of the response body.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] In our basic fetch example (run example live) we use a simple `fetch()` call to grab an image and display it in an `<img>` element.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] The `fetch()` call returns a promise, which resolves to the `Response` object associated with the resource fetch operation.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] You'll notice that since we are requesting an image, we need to run `Response.blob` to give the response its correct MIME type.
[src:ky-fetch/api-response] Here we call a PHP program file that generates a JSON string, displaying the result as a JSON value.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In computer science, **futures**, **promises**, **delays**, and **deferreds** are constructs used for synchronizing program execution in some concurrent programming languages.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Each is an object that acts as a proxy for a result that is initially unknown, usually because the computation of its value is not yet complete.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was proposed in 1976 by Daniel P.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Friedman and David Wise, and Peter Hibbard called it *eventual*.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] A somewhat similar concept *future* was introduced in 1977 in a paper by Henry Baker and Carl Hewitt.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The terms *future*, *promise*, *delay*, and *deferred* are often used interchangeably, although there can be some differences in usage between *future* and *promise*.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Specifically, when usage is distinguished, a future is a *read-only* placeholder view of a variable, while a promise is a writable, single assignment container which sets the value of the future.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Notably, a future may be defined without specifying which specific promise will set its value, and different possible promises may set the value of a given future, though this can be done only once for a given future.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In other cases a future and a promise are created together and associated with each other: the future is the value, the promise is the function that sets the value – essentially the return value (future) of an asynchronous function (promise).
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Setting the value of a future is also called *resolving*, *fulfilling*, or *binding* it.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Futures and promises originated in functional programming and related paradigms (such as logic programming) to decouple a value (a future) from how it was computed (a promise), allowing the computation to be done more flexibly, notably by parallelizing it.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Later, it found use in distributed computing, in reducing the latency from communication round trips.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Later still, it gained more use by allowing writing asynchronous programs in direct style, rather than in continuation-passing style.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Use of futures may be *implicit* (any use of the future automatically obtains its value, as if it were an ordinary reference) or *explicit* (the user must call a function to obtain the value, such as the `get` method of `java.util.concurrent.Future`in Java).
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Obtaining the value of an explicit future can be called *stinging* or *forcing*.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Explicit futures can be implemented as a library, whereas implicit futures are usually implemented as part of the language.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The original Baker and Hewitt paper described implicit futures, which are naturally supported in the actor model of computation and pure object-oriented programming languages like Smalltalk.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The Friedman and Wise paper described only explicit futures, probably reflecting the difficulty of efficiently implementing implicit futures on stock hardware.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The difficulty is that stock hardware does not deal with futures for primitive data types like integers.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] For example, an add instruction does not know how to deal with `3 + *future* factorial(100000)`.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In pure actor or object languages this problem can be solved by sending `*future* factorial(100000)` the message `+[3]`, which asks the future to add `3` to itself and return the result.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Note that the message passing approach works regardless of when `factorial(100000)` finishes computation and that no stinging/forcing is needed.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The use of futures can dramatically reduce latency in distributed systems.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] For instance, futures enable *promise pipelining*, as implemented in the languages E and Joule, which was also called *call-stream* in the language Argus.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Each statement needs a message to be sent and a reply received before the next statement can proceed.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Suppose, for example, that `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In this case, two complete network round-trips to that machine must take place before the third statement can begin to execute.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The third statement will then cause yet another round-trip to the same remote machine.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The syntax used here is that of the language E, where `x <- a()` means to send the message `a()` asynchronously to `x`.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] All three variables are immediately assigned futures for their results, and execution proceeds to subsequent statements.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Later attempts to resolve the value of `t3` may cause a delay; however, pipelining can reduce the number of round-trips needed.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] If, as in the prior example, `x`, `y`, `t1`, and `t2` are all located on the same remote machine, a pipelined implementation can compute `t3` with one round-trip instead of three.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Because all three messages are destined for objects which are on the same remote machine, only one request need be sent and only one response need be received containing the result.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The send `t1 <- c(t2)` would not block even if `t1` and `t2` were on different machines to each other, or to `x` or `y`.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining should be distinguished from parallel asynchronous message passing.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The relative latency advantage of pipelining becomes even greater in more complicated situations involving many messages.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Promise pipelining also should not be confused with pipelined message processing in actor systems, where it is possible for an actor to specify and begin executing a behaviour for the next message before having completed processing of the current message.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Support for read-only views is consistent with the principle of least privilege, since it enables the ability to set the value to be restricted to subjects that need to set it.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In a system that also supports pipelining, the sender of an asynchronous message (with result) receives the read-only promise for the result, and the target of the message receives the resolver.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Some languages, such as Alice ML, define futures that are associated with a specific thread that computes the future's value.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] This computation can start either eagerly when the future is created, or lazily when its value is first needed.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] A lazy future is similar to a thunk, in the sense of a delayed computation.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Alice ML also supports futures that can be resolved by any thread, and calls these *promises*.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] This use of *promise* is different from its use in E as described above.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In Alice, a promise is not a read-only view, and promise pipelining is unsupported.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Instead, pipelining naturally happens for futures, including ones associated with promises.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] If the value of a future is accessed asynchronously, for example by sending a message to it, or by explicitly waiting for it using a construct such as `when` in E, then there is no difficulty in delaying until the future is resolved before the message can be received or the wait completes.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] This is the only case to be considered in purely asynchronous systems such as pure actor languages.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] However, in some systems it may also be possible to attempt to *immediately* or *synchronously* access a future's value.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] As an example of the first possibility, in C++11, a thread that needs the value of a future can block until it is available by calling the `wait()` or `get()` member functions.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] A timeout can also be specified on the wait using the `wait_for()` or `wait_until()` member functions to avoid indefinite blocking.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] If the future arose from a call to `std::async` then a blocking wait (without a timeout) may cause synchronous invocation of the function to compute the result on the waiting thread.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] An *I-var* (as in the language Id) is a future with blocking semantics as defined above.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] An *I-structure* is a data structure containing I-vars.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] A related synchronization construct that can be set multiple times with different values is called an *M-var*.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] M-vars support atomic operations to *take* or *put* the current value, where taking the value also sets the M-var back to its initial *empty* state.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent logic variable* is similar to a future, but is updated by unification, in the same way as *logic variables* in logic programming.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Thus it can be bound more than once to unifiable values, but cannot be set back to an empty or unresolved state.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The dataflow variables of Oz act as concurrent logic variables, and also have blocking semantics as mentioned above.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] A *concurrent constraint variable* is a generalization of concurrent logic variables to support constraint logic programming: the constraint may be *narrowed* multiple times, indicating smaller sets of possible values.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Typically there is a way to specify a thunk that should run whenever the constraint is narrowed further; this is needed to support *constraint propagation*.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Eager thread-specific futures can be straightforwardly implemented in non-thread-specific futures, by creating a thread to calculate the value at the same time as creating the future.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In this case it is desirable to return a read-only view to the client, so that only the newly created thread is able to resolve this future.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] To implement implicit lazy thread-specific futures (as provided by Alice ML, for example) in terms in non-thread-specific futures, needs a mechanism to determine when the future's value is first needed (for example, the `WaitNeeded` construct in Oz).
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] If all values are objects, then the ability to implement transparent forwarding objects is sufficient, since the first message sent to the forwarder indicates that the future's value is needed.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Non-thread-specific futures can be implemented in thread-specific futures, assuming that the system supports message passing, by having the resolving thread send a message to the future's own thread.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] However, this can be viewed as unneeded complexity.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] In programming languages based on threads, the most expressive approach seems to be to provide a mix of non-thread-specific futures, read-only views, and either a *WaitNeeded* construct, or support for transparent forwarding.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The evaluation strategy of futures, which may be termed *call by future*, is non-deterministic: the value of a future will be evaluated at some time between when the future is created and when its value is used, but the precise time is not determined beforehand and can change from run to run.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The computation can start as soon as the future is created (eager evaluation) or only when the value is actually needed (lazy evaluation), and may be suspended part-way through, or executed in one run.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Once the value of a future is assigned, it is not recomputed on future accesses; this is like the memoization used in call by need.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] A **lazy future** is a future that deterministically has lazy evaluation semantics: the computation of the future's value starts when the value is first needed, as in call by need.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Lazy futures are of use in languages which evaluation strategy is by default not lazy.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] For example, in C++11 such lazy futures can be created by passing the `std::launch::deferred` launch policy to `std::async`, along with the function to compute the value.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] If it does not already have a response, then *R* is stored in the queue of requests inside the *F*.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] However, some futures can deal with requests in special ways to provide greater parallelism.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] For example, the expression `1 + future factorial(n)` can create a new future that will behave like the number `1+factorial(n)`.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] suspends until the future for `factorial(n)` has responded to the request asking if `m` is greater than itself.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The *future* and/or *promise* constructs were first implemented in programming languages such as MultiLisp and Act 1.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The use of logic variables for communication in concurrent logic programming languages was quite similar to futures.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] These began in *Prolog with Freeze* and *IC Prolog*, and became a true concurrency primitive with Relational Language, Concurrent Prolog, guarded Horn clauses (GHC), Parlog, Strand, Vulcan, Janus, Oz-Mozart, Flow Java, and Alice ML.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The single-assignment *I-var* from dataflow programming languages, originating in Id and included in Reppy's *Concurrent ML*, is much like the concurrent logic variable.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The promise pipelining technique (using futures to overcome latency) was invented by Barbara Liskov and Liuba Shrira in 1988, and independently by Mark S.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Miller, Dean Tribble and Rob Jellinghaus in the context of Project Xanadu circa 1989.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The term *promise* was coined by Liskov and Shrira, although they referred to the pipelining mechanism by the name *call-stream*, which is now rarely used.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] It seems that promises and call-streams were never implemented in any public release of Argus, the programming language used in the Liskov and Shrira paper.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The Xanadu implementation of promise pipelining only became publicly available with the release of the source code for Udanax Gold in 1999, and was never explained in any published document.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The later implementations in Joule and E support fully first-class promises and resolvers.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Several early actor languages, including the Act series, supported both parallel message passing and pipelined message processing, but not promise pipelining.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] After 2000, a major revival of interest in futures and promises occurred, due to their use in responsiveness of user interfaces, and in web development, due to the request–response model of message-passing.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] This has subsequently been adopted by other languages, notably Dart (2014), Python (2015), Hack (HHVM), and drafts of ECMAScript 7 (JavaScript), Scala, and C++ (2011).
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Some programming languages are supporting futures, promises, concurrent logic variables, dataflow variables, or I-vars, either by direct language support or in the standard library.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Futures can be implemented in coroutines or generators, resulting in the same evaluation strategy (e.g., cooperative multitasking or lazy evaluation).
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] Futures can easily be implemented in channels: a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] This allows futures to be implemented in concurrent programming languages with support for channels, such as CSP and Go.
[src:ky-fetch/futures-and-promises] The resulting futures are explicit, as they must be accessed by reading from the channel, rather than only evaluation.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:ky-fetch/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Sindre's open source work is supported by the community.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] AI-powered meeting notes, automations, and search.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Give AI agents the context they need to get things done.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Ky targets modern browsers, Node.js, Bun, and Deno.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It's just a tiny package with no dependencies.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This readme is for the next version of Ky.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If you are using Deno, import Ky from a URL.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `input` and `options` are the same as `fetch`, with additional `options` available (see below).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Returns a `Response` object with `Body` methods added for convenience.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] So you can, for example, call `ky.get(input).json()` directly without having to await the `Response` first.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] When called like that, an appropriate `Accept` header will be set depending on the body method used.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Unlike the `Body` methods of `window.fetch`, these will throw an `HTTPError` if the response status is not in the range of `200...299`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Also, `.json()` throws if the body is empty or the response status is `204`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `.bytes()` shortcut is only present when the runtime supports `Response.prototype.bytes()`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] ⌨️ **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional type parameter, which defaults to `unknown`, and is passed through to the return type of `.json()`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can also get the response body as JSON and validate it with a Standard Schema compatible validator (for example, Zod 3.24+).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This throws a `SchemaValidationError` when validation fails.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Sets `options.method` to the method name and makes a request.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] ⌨️ **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional type parameter for use with JSON responses (see `ky()`).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] When using a `Request` instance as `input`, any URL altering options (such as `baseUrl`) will be ignored.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Internally, the standard methods (`GET`, `POST`, `PUT`, `PATCH`, `HEAD` and `DELETE`) are uppercased in order to avoid server errors due to case sensitivity.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Accepts any plain object or value, which will be stringified using `JSON.stringify()` and sent in the body with the correct header set.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Search parameters to include in the request URL.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Setting this will merge with any existing search parameters in the input URL.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Accepts any value supported by `URLSearchParams()`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] When passing an object, setting a value to `undefined` deletes the parameter, while `null` values are preserved and converted to the string `'null'`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] A base URL to resolve the `input` against.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] When the `input` (after applying the `prefix` option) is only a relative URL, such as `'users'`, `'/users'`, or `'//my-site.com'`, it will be resolved against the `baseUrl` to determine the destination of the request.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Otherwise, the `input` is absolute, such as `'https://my-site.com'`, and it will bypass the `baseUrl`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Useful when used with `ky.extend()` to create niche-specific Ky instances.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If the `baseUrl` itself is relative, it will be resolved against the environment's base URL, such as `document.baseURI` in browsers or `location.href` in Deno (see the `--location` flag).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] A prefix to prepend to the `input` before making the request (and before it is resolved against the `baseUrl`).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It can be any valid path or URL, either relative or absolute.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] A trailing slash `/` is optional and will be added automatically, if needed, when it is joined with `input`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Only takes effect when `input` is a string.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Each field is documented individually below.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If `retry` is a number, it will be used as `limit` and other defaults will remain in place.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Network errors (e.g., DNS failures, connection refused, offline) are automatically retried for retriable methods.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Only errors recognized as network errors are retried; other errors (e.g., programming bugs) are thrown immediately.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Use `shouldRetry` to customize this behavior.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If the response provides an HTTP status contained in `afterStatusCodes`, Ky will wait until the date, delay, or timestamp given in the `Retry-After` header has passed to retry the request.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If `Retry-After` is missing, the non-standard `RateLimit-Reset` header is used in its place as a fallback.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If the provided status code is not in the list, the `Retry-After` header will be ignored.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If `Retry-After` header is greater than `maxRetryAfter`, it will use `maxRetryAfter`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `backoffLimit` option is the upper limit of the delay per retry in milliseconds.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] To clamp the delay, set `backoffLimit` to 1000, for example.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] By default, the delay is calculated with `0.3 * (2 ** (attemptCount - 1)) * 1000`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `delay` option can be used to change how the delay between retries is calculated.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The function receives one parameter, the attempt count, starting at `1`, and must return the delay in milliseconds.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `jitter` option adds random jitter to retry delays to prevent thundering herd problems.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] When many clients retry simultaneously (e.g., after hitting a rate limit), they can overwhelm the server again.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Jitter adds randomness to break this synchronization.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Set to `true` to use full jitter, which randomizes the delay between 0 and the computed delay.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Alternatively, pass a function to implement custom jitter strategies.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `retryOnTimeout` option determines whether to retry when a request times out.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] By default, retries are not triggered following a timeout.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `shouldRetry` option provides custom retry logic that **takes precedence over the default retry checks** (`retryOnTimeout`, status code checks, etc.) for retriable methods.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It is only called after the retry limit and method checks pass.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] When retries are enabled, Ky clones the request body before each attempt using `tee()`, which buffers the entire `ReadableStream` in memory.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Set `retry: {limit: 0}` if you're uploading large streaming bodies and don't need retries.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Chromium-based browsers automatically retry `408 Request Timeout` responses at the network layer for keep-alive connections.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This means requests may be retried by both the browser and ky.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If you want to avoid duplicate retries, you can either set `keepalive: false` in your request options (though this may impact performance for multiple requests) or remove `408` from the retry status codes.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Per-attempt timeout in milliseconds for getting a response, applied independently to each retry.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If set to `false`, there will be no per-attempt timeout.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Overall timeout in milliseconds for the entire operation, including retries and delays.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If set to `false` or not specified, there is no overall timeout.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Hooks allow modifications during the request lifecycle.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Hook functions may be async and are run serially, unless otherwise noted.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This hook enables you to modify the options before they are used to construct the request.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The hook function receives the mutable options object and can modify it in place.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You could, for example, modify `searchParams`, `headers`, or `json` here.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Unlike other hooks, `init` hooks are synchronous.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Any error thrown will propagate synchronously and will not be caught by `beforeError` hooks.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This hook enables you to modify the request right before it is sent.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Ky will make no further changes to the request after this.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The hook function receives a state object with the normalized request, options, and retry count.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You could, for example, modify `request.headers` here.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `retryCount` is always `0`, since `beforeRequest` hooks run once before retry handling begins.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The hook can return a `Request` to replace the outgoing request (remaining hooks will still run with the updated request).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It can also return a `Response` to completely avoid making an HTTP request, in which case remaining `beforeRequest` hooks are skipped.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This can be used to mock a request, check an internal cache, etc.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Any error thrown by `beforeRequest` hooks is treated as fatal and will not trigger Ky's retry logic.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This hook enables you to modify the request right before retry.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The hook function receives a state object with the normalized request, options, an error instance, and retry count.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The hook can return a `Request` to replace the outgoing retry request, or return a `Response` to skip the retry and use that response instead.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] **Note:** Returning a request or response skips remaining `beforeRetry` hooks.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Returned `Request` objects are used as-is.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If you point one at another origin, remove any credentials you do not want forwarded.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `retryCount` is always `>= 1`, since this hook is only called during retries, not on the initial request.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If the request received a response, the error will be of type `HTTPError`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `Response` object will be available at `error.response`, and the pre-parsed response body will be available at `error.data`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Be aware that some types of errors, such as network errors, inherently mean that a response was not received.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] In that case, the error will be an instance of `NetworkError` instead of `HTTPError`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can prevent Ky from retrying the request by throwing an error.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Ky will not handle it in any way and the error will be propagated to the request initiator.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The rest of the `beforeRetry` hooks will not be called in this case.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Alternatively, you can return the `ky.stop` symbol to do the same thing but without propagating an error (this has some limitations, see `ky.stop` docs for details).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This hook enables you to modify any error right before it is thrown.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The hook function receives a state object with the current request, the normalized Ky options, the error, and retry count, and should return an `Error` instance.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This hook is called for all error types, including `HTTPError`, `NetworkError`, `TimeoutError`, and `ForceRetryError` (when retry limit is exceeded via `ky.retry()`).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Use type guards like `isHTTPError()`, `isNetworkError()`, or `isTimeoutError()` to handle specific error types.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `retryCount` is `0` for the initial request and increments with each retry.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This allows you to distinguish between the initial request and retries, which is useful when you need different error handling based on retry attempts (e.g., showing different error messages on the final attempt).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If a `beforeRequest` or `beforeRetry` hook returns a new `Request`, inspect `request` for the final request state.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] `options` remains Ky's normalized options and may not mirror every property of a replacement `Request`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This hook enables you to read and optionally modify the response.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The hook function receives a state object with the normalized request, options, a clone of the response, and retry count.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The return value of the hook function will be used by Ky as the response object if it's an instance of `Response`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can also force a retry by returning `ky.retry(options)`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This is useful when you need to retry based on the response body content, even if the response has a successful status code.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The retry will respect the `retry.limit` option and be observable in `beforeRetry` hooks.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] `ky.retry({request})` uses the replacement request as-is.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If it targets another origin, remove any credentials you do not want forwarded.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Any non-`ky.retry()` error thrown by `afterResponse` hooks is treated as fatal and will not trigger Ky's retry logic.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This allows you to distinguish between the initial request and retries, which is useful when you need different behavior for retries (e.g., showing a notification only on the final retry).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Throw an `HTTPError` when, after following redirects, the response has a non-2xx status code.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] To also throw for redirects instead of following them, set the `redirect` option to `'manual'`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Setting this to `false` may be useful if you are checking for resource availability and are expecting error responses.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can also pass a function that accepts the HTTP status code and returns a boolean for selective error handling.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Note that this can violate the principle of least surprise, so it's recommended to use the boolean form unless you have a specific use case like treating 404 responses differently.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Note: If `false`, error responses are considered successful and the request will not be retried.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Note: Opaque responses from `no-cors` requests are returned as-is (without throwing `HTTPError`), since the actual status is hidden by the browser.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Requires request stream support and HTTP/2 for HTTPS connections (in Chromium-based browsers).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] In unsupported environments, this handler is silently ignored.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The function receives the response text as the first argument and a context object as the second argument containing the `request` (`Request`) and `response` (`Response`).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Parse JSON with `reviver` option of `JSON.parse()`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Log or handle JSON parse errors with request context.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] User-defined JSON-stringifying function.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Has to be fully compatible with the Fetch API standard.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Add custom instrumentation or logging to all requests.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This option allows you to pass arbitrary contextual data to hooks without polluting the request itself.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The context is available in all hooks and is **guaranteed to always be an object** (never `undefined`), so you can safely access properties without optional chaining.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Create a new `ky` instance with some defaults overridden with your own.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] In contrast to `ky.create()`, `ky.extend()` inherits defaults from its parent.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can pass headers as a `Headers` instance or a plain object.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can remove a header with `.extend()` by passing the header with an `undefined` value.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Passing `undefined` as a string removes the header only if it comes from a `Headers` instance.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Similarly, you can remove existing `hooks` entries by extending the hook with an explicit `undefined`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can also refer to parent defaults by providing a function to `.extend()`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] By default, `.extend()` deep-merges options: hooks are appended, headers are merged, and search parameters are accumulated.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Use `replaceOption` when you want to fully replace a merged property instead.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Create a new Ky instance with complete new defaults, without inheriting from any parent instance.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] A `Symbol` that can be returned by a `beforeRetry` hook to stop the retry.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This will also short circuit the remaining `beforeRetry` hooks.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Note: Returning this symbol makes Ky abort and return with an `undefined` response.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Be sure to check for a response before accessing any properties on it or use optional chaining.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It is also incompatible with body methods, such as `.json()` or `.text()`, because there is no response to parse.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] In general, we recommend throwing an error instead of returning this symbol, as that will cause Ky to abort and then throw, which avoids these limitations.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] A valid use-case for `ky.stop` is to prevent retries when making requests for side effects, where the returned data is not important.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] For example, logging client activity to the server.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Force a retry from an `afterResponse` hook.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This allows you to retry a request based on the response content, even if the response has a successful status code.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The retry will respect the `retry.limit` option and skip the `shouldRetry` check.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The forced retry is observable in `beforeRetry` hooks, where the error will be a `ForceRetryError`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Custom delay in milliseconds before retrying.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If not provided, uses the default retry delay calculation based on `retry.delay` configuration.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This machine-readable identifier will be included in the error message passed to `beforeRetry` hooks, allowing you to distinguish between different types of forced retries.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This allows you to preserve the error chain when forcing a retry based on caught exceptions.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The error will be set as the `cause` of the `ForceRetryError`, enabling proper error chain traversal.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This allows you to modify or completely replace the request during a forced retry.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The custom request becomes the starting point for the retry - `beforeRetry` hooks can still further modify it if needed.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Custom retry requests are not sanitized.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If you reuse headers across origins, remove any credentials you do not want forwarded.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] `HTTPError`, `NetworkError`, `TimeoutError`, and `ForceRetryError` extend this class.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] You can use `instanceof KyError` to check if an error originated from Ky, or use the `isKyError()` type guard for cross-realm compatibility and TypeScript type narrowing.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] `SchemaValidationError` is intentionally not considered a Ky error.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] `KyError` covers failures in Ky's HTTP lifecycle (bad status, timeout, retry), while schema validation errors originate from the user-provided schema, not from Ky itself.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The error has a `response` property with the `Response` object, `request` property with the `Request` object, and `options` property with normalized options (either passed to `ky` when creating an instance with `ky.create()` or directly when performing the request).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It also has a `data` property with the pre-parsed response body.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] For JSON responses (based on `Content-Type`), the body is parsed using the `parseJson` option if set, or `JSON.parse` by default.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] For other content types, it is set as plain text.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] If the body is empty or parsing fails, `data` will be `undefined`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] To avoid hanging or excessive buffering, `error.data` population is bounded by the request timeout and a 10 MiB response body size limit.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `data` property is populated before `beforeError` hooks run, so hooks can access it.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] In that case, the error will be an instance of `NetworkError` instead of `HTTPError` and will not contain a `response` property.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The response body is automatically consumed when populating `error.data`, so `error.response.json()` and other body methods will not work.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The `error.response` object is still available for headers, status, etc.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] ⌨️ **TypeScript:** Accepts an optional type parameter, which defaults to `unknown`, and is passed through to the type of `error.data`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The error thrown when Standard Schema validation fails in `.json(schema)`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It has an `issues` property with the validation issues from the schema.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] This error intentionally does not extend `KyError` because it does not represent a failure in Ky's HTTP lifecycle.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The request succeeded; the user's schema rejected the data.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] As such, it is not matched by `isKyError()`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The error thrown when the request times out.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] It has a `request` property with the `Request` object.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The error thrown when a network error occurs during the request (e.g., DNS failure, connection refused, offline).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] The original error is available via the standard `cause` property.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Network errors are automatically retried (for retriable methods).
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Network errors are detected using runtime-specific heuristics.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Unrecognized runtimes may produce errors that are not wrapped in `NetworkError`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Use the `shouldRetry` option to handle such cases.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Wraps a value so that `ky.extend()` will replace the parent value instead of merging with it.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p01] Works with hooks, headers, search parameters, context, and any other deep-merged option.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Sending form data in Ky is identical to `fetch`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Just pass a `FormData` instance to the `body` option.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] The `Content-Type` header will be automatically set to `multipart/form-data`, overriding any existing `Content-Type` header.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] If you want to send the data in `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` format, you will need to encode the data with `URLSearchParams`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Like `FormData`, this will override any existing `Content-Type` headers.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Ky automatically sets an appropriate `Content-Type` header for each request based on the data in the request body.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] However, some APIs require custom, non-standard content types, such as `application/x-amz-json-1.1`.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Using the `headers` option, you can manually override the content type.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Fetch (and hence Ky) has built-in support for request cancellation through the `AbortController` API.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Node.js 24.5+ supports automatic proxy configuration via environment variables.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Set `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1` or use the `--use-env-proxy` CLI flag.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] For more control, use `ProxyAgent` or `EnvHttpProxyAgent` with the `dispatcher` option.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Undici supports HTTP/2, but it's not enabled by default.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] To send a `ReadableStream` as the request body, you must pass `duplex: 'half'` per the Fetch spec.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Ky can't set this automatically as it changes request semantics for all requests, not just streaming ones.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] When retries are enabled (the default), Ky buffers the entire streaming body in memory to support replaying it.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Set `retry: {limit: 0}` to skip this if retries aren't needed.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] Ky's TypeScript types are intentionally defined as type aliases rather than interfaces to prevent global module augmentation, which can lead to type conflicts and unexpected behavior across your codebase.
[src:ky-fetch/sindresorhus-ky-p02] This approach keeps your types scoped to where they're needed without polluting the global namespace.
